                Robert L. Nardelli            


News about Robert L. Nardelli, including commentary and archival articles published in The New York Times.                    








Latest Articles






DEALBOOK

                    A Cerberus Executive Resigns From Most of His Company Roles                
Robert L. Nardelli is ending his formal ties to Cerberus Capital Management, the private equity firm that installed him as the chief executive of Chrysler nearly two years before the carmaker filed for bankruptcy. In a statement on Friday, Cerberus said that Mr. Nardelli had stepped down as the chief executive of Cerberus Operations and Advisory Company, or COAC, a unit of the firm that provides management and operations advice to Cerberus portfolio companies. Mr. Nardelli is also resigning as the chief executive of the Freedom Group, the sprawling conglomeration of gun makers that includes Remington Arms and Bushmaster Firearms, which is also owned by Cerberus.










DealBook

                    Former Chief of CVS Caremark Joins Private Equity Firm                
Thomas Ryan, a former chief executive of CVS Caremark, has joined the private equity firm Advent International as an operating partner.










DealBook

                    The Gift of Guns, Courtesy of Cerberus                
For employees of AlixPartners, finding a last-minute holiday gift may have gotten a little easier.










DealBook

                    Cerberus's Freedom Names Nardelli as Chief                
Robert L. Nardelli has taken the helm of yet another portfolio company of Cerberus Capital Management, assuming on Friday the role of head of the gun maker Freedom Group's newly created office of the chief executive.











                    Ex-Duracell Chairman to Lead New Chrysler                
C. Robert Kidder will succeed Robert L. Nardelli, who will step down when Chrysler emerges from Chapter 11.











                    Chrysler’s Chief Says He Believes He Has Saved the Automaker                
President Obama singled out Robert Nardelli for his “positive and constructive role” in getting deals with Fiat, the United Automobile Workers, and Chrysler’s largest lenders that will be integral to a successful restructuring in bankruptcy court.










TimesVideo

                    Fueling Chrysler's Future                
The automaker's C.E.O. Robert Nardelli discusses what's in store for the future, with CNBC's Maria Bartiromo.

















                    Nardelli, Defying Skeptics, Digs In to Save Chrysler                
Robert L. Nardelli said he fears consumers would shun Chrysler's cars, trucks and sport utility vehicles if the company sought court protection.










Slide Show

                    Seeking Bailout, Automakers Return to Capitol Hill                
The chiefs of the Big Three automakers and the United Auto Workers were back on Capitol Hill to plead for federal cash.











                    Auto Chiefs Fail to Get Bailout Aid                
The Big Three automakers left Washington empty-handed after two days of pleading for a financial lifeline.















                    Chrysler Explores Sale of Dodge Viper Unit                
The automaker said it was considering options for the sports car unit as it tries to raise cash to ride out a deepening industry downturn in the United States.











                    Owner Gives Executives Time to Fix Chrysler                
Top Chrysler executives are determined to fix the company, and executives at Cerberus Capital, Chrysler’s new private-equity owner, say they will get the chance.











                    Chrysler Announces Design Chief to Retire                
Chrysler said the design chief responsible for the success of the Dodge Challenger, Chrysler PT Cruiser, Dodge Viper and Dodge Ram is retiring at month’s end.










TimesVideo

                    Bob Nardelli on Chrysler's Path                
CNBC's Phil Lebeau shares the highlights of his interview with Bob Nardelli, Chrysler's chief executive.
















Suits

                    Some Offstage Help for Apollo Theater                
Richard D. Parsons, chairman of Time Warner and a Brooklyn native, has been a patron of the Apollo Theater in Harlem since his high school days. The first act he saw there was the Jackson Five.











                    Will Nardelli Be Chrysler’s Mr. Fix-It?                
A Detroit outsider faces an industry slump and a tough economy.











                    In 2007, Some Giants Went Smaller                
Bigger is better, right? Not so fast. Corporate America appears to have had second thoughts in 2007.











                    Job Cuts at Chrysler Go Even Deeper Than Expected                
Thursday’s cuts, together with a previously announced elimination of 13,000 positions, represent a 30 percent reduction in Chrysler’s 2006 work force.











                    At Chrysler, Home Depot Still Lingers                
Robert L. Nardelli, Chrysler’s new chief who earlier ran Home Depot, spoke about the auto industry in terms that suggested he was still in a home-improvement state of mind.











                    Chrysler Chief Calls Pay Pact Revolutionary                
Saying he is not concerned by the level of opposition to Chrysler’s new two-tier wage system, the company’s new chief executive called the contract ‘a major step forward.’










